.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** coins = [[8,10,1],[1,3,2],[5,6,4]], k = 4\n\n**Output:** 10\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nSelecting bags at positions `[3, 4, 5, 6]` gives the maximum number of coins: `2 + 0 + 4 + 4 = 10`.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** coins = [[1,10,3]], k = 2\n\n**Output:** 6\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nSelecting bags at positions `[1, 2]` gives the maximum number of coins: `3 + 3 = 6`.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= coins.length <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= k <= 10⁹`\n\n- `coins[i] == [li, ri, ci]`\n\n- `1 <= li <= ri <= 10⁹`\n\n- `1 <= ci <= 1000`\n\n- The given segments are non-overlapping.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-coins-from-k-consecutive-bags/","problemName":"Maximum Coins From K Consecutive Bags","problemNumber":3413,"problemSlug":"maximum-coins-from-k-consecutive-bags","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":3413,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Binary Search","Dynamic Programming","Sorting"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given a 2D integer array `intervals`, where `intervals[i] = [li, ri, weighti]`. Interval `i` starts at position `li` and ends at `ri`, and has a weight of `weighti`. You can choose *up to* 4 **non-overlapping** intervals. The **score** of the chosen intervals is defined as the total sum of their weights.\n\nReturn the [lexicographically smallest](leetcode-keyword) array of at most 4 indices from `intervals` with **maximum** score, representing your choice of non-overlapping intervals.\n\nTwo intervals are said to be **non-overlapping** if they do not share any points. In particular, intervals sharing a left or right boundary are considered overlapping.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** intervals = [[1,3,2],[4,5,2],[1,5,5],[6,9,3],[6,7,1],[8,9,1]]\n\n**Output:** [2,3]\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nYou can choose the intervals with indices 2, and 3 with respective weights of 5, and 3.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** intervals = [[5,8,1],[6,7,7],[4,7,3],[9,10,6],[7